05175nam a22009375i 9780520941465DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20062006cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209414657 a10.1525/97805209414652doi  a(DE-B1597)519601  a(OCoLC)63813517  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aZ186.J3bB47 2006eb 7aHIS0030002bisacsh04a686.2/0952/09090322221 aBerry, Mary Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJapan in Print :bInformation and Nation in the Early Modern Period /cMary Elizabeth Berry. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2006] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (342 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsia: Local Studies / Global Themes ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. A Traveling Clerk Goes to the Bookstores -- t2. The Library of Public Information -- t3. Maps Are Strange -- t4. Blood Right and Merit -- t5. The Freedom of the City -- t6. Cultural Custody, Cultural Literacy -- t7. Nation -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA quiet revolution in knowledge separated the early modern period in Japan from all previous time. After 1600, self-appointed investigators used the model of the land and cartographic surveys of the newly unified state to observe and order subjects such as agronomy, medicine, gastronomy, commerce, travel, and entertainment. They subsequently circulated their findings through a variety of commercially printed texts: maps, gazetteers, family encyclopedias, urban directories, travel guides, official personnel rosters, and instruction manuals for everything from farming to lovemaking. In this original and gracefully written book, Mary Elizabeth Berry considers the social processes that drove the information explosion of the 1600s. Inviting readers to examine the contours and meanings of this transformation, Berry provides a fascinating account of the conversion of the public from an object of state surveillance into a subject of self-knowledge.Japan in Print shows how, as investigators collected and disseminated richly diverse data, they came to presume in their audience a standard of cultural literacy that changed anonymous consumers into an "us" bound by common frames of reference. This shared space of knowledge made society visible to itself and in the process subverted notions of status hierarchy. Berry demonstrates that the new public texts projected a national collectivity characterized by universal access to markets, mobility, sociability, and self-fashioning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPrintingzJapanxHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  aagronomy.  aasian history.  acartography.  acommerce.  acommon frames of reference.  acommunication.  acultural literacy.  adiverse data.  aearly modern japan.  aearly modern period.  aeast asian culture.  aentertainment.  agastronomy.  ajapan.  ajapanese culture.  ajapanese society.  amarkets.  amaterial culture.  amedia studies.  amedicine.  amobility.  amodel of the land.  anational collectivity.  aprint culture.  aself fashioning.  aself knowledge.  asociability.  astate surveillance.  astatus hierarchy.  atravel.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023766740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094146540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520941465423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/978052094